      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
        </div>
        <div purpose="faq" class="d-flex flex-column">
          <div purpose="accordion" class="d-flex flex-column justify-content-start">
            <div purpose="accordion-body">
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header1" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body1" aria-controls="os-faq__body1">
                  What is open-source MDM?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body1" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header1">
                  Open-source mobile device management (MDM) is endpoint management software whose source code is publicly available to inspect, modify, and contribute to. Unlike proprietary MDM platforms, organizations can review exactly how their devices are managed, host the software themselves, and adapt it to their needs.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header2" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body2" aria-controls="os-faq__body2">
                  Is Fleet truly open source?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body2" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header2">
                  Yes. The majority of Fleet is released under the MIT license, and all of Fleet's source code is public on GitHub at <a href="https://github.com/fleetdm/fleet" target="_blank">github.com/fleetdm/fleet</a>. Documentation lives under a Creative Commons (CC BY-SA 4.0) license. A separate set of paid features lives in an <code>/ee</code> directory under a commercial license.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header3" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body3" aria-controls="os-faq__body3">
                  How does open-source endpoint management compare to traditional MDM?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body3" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header3">
                  Traditional MDM platforms are proprietary, cloud-only, and built primarily for one OS family. Open-source endpoint management like Fleet is multi-platform, API-first, manageable as code through GitOps, and inspectable by IT, security, and end users. Fleet has no vendor lock-in: teams can self-host, switch to managed cloud, or move data between environments without rebuilding their stack.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header4" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body4" aria-controls="os-faq__body4">
                  Which operating systems does Fleet support?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body4" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header4">
                  Fleet is a single endpoint management platform for macOS, iOS, Android, Windows, Linux, ChromeOS, and cloud infrastructure. Mixed Apple, Windows, Linux, and Android fleets are managed from one console, with the same UI, API, and infrastructure-as-code workflows for every platform.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header5" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body5" aria-controls="os-faq__body5">
                  Does Fleet's open-source MDM work on Linux?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body5" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header5">
                  Yes. Fleet provides full <a href="/linux-management">Linux device management</a>, including remote scripting, software install and patch automation, configuration management, and real-time visibility. Supported distributions include Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, Amazon Linux, CentOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL), openSUSE, and Arch Linux. Fleet handles both Debian-based (.deb) and RPM-based (.rpm) packages, and Fleet Desktop runs on GNOME and KDE Plasma.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header6" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body6" aria-controls="os-faq__body6">
                  Can Fleet be self-hosted?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body6" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header6">
                  Yes. Fleet can be deployed <a href="/on-premise">on-premises</a>, in any major cloud (AWS, Azure, GCP, DigitalOcean), in containers (Docker, or Kubernetes via Helm or Terraform), or in air-gapped environments. Teams that prefer a managed option can choose Fleet Cloud and get the same experience either way.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header7" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body7" aria-controls="os-faq__body7">
                  What infrastructure does a self-hosted Fleet deployment need?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body7" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header7">
                  Fleet has three infrastructure dependencies: a MySQL database, a Redis-compatible cache (Redis or Valkey), and a TLS certificate. A single Fleet server can handle tens of thousands of hosts, and deployments scale horizontally to hundreds of thousands of devices behind a load balancer.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div purpose="accordion-item">
                <p purpose="accordion-header" id="os-faq__header8" style="cursor: pointer;" class="accordion" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#os-faq__body8" aria-controls="os-faq__body8">
                  What is the difference between Fleet free and Fleet Premium?
                  <span class="fa fa-angle-down"></span>
                </p>
                <p purpose="faq-answer" id="os-faq__body8" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="os-faq__header8">
                  Both are open source and available on GitHub. The free version, under the MIT license, includes core open-source MDM, osquery management, and infrastructure-as-code workflows, and it can be downloaded without leaving an email address. Fleet Premium adds paid features (under a separate license in the <code>/ee</code> directory) and includes professional support with a guaranteed response time.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="d-flex flex-row justify-content-start">
              <p purpose="contact-note">Have another question? <a href="/docs/get-started/faq">Read the full FAQ</a> or <a href="/contact">talk to an engineer</a>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
